SIMPLE: push
RECORDS: 5

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Push
<hw>Push</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Probably F.
<ets>poche</ets>. See <er>Pouch</er>.]</ety> <def>A pustule; a
pimple.</def> <mark>[Obs. or Prov. Eng.]</mark>
<rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Push</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Push
<hw>Push</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Pushed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Pushing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>possen</ets>,
<ets>pussen</ets>, F. <ets>pousser</ets>, fr. L. <ets>pulsare</ets>, v.
intens. fr. <ets>pellere</ets>, <ets>pulsum</ets>, to beat, knock, push.
See <er>Pulse</er> a beating, and cf. <er>Pursy</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To press against with force; to drive or impel by pressure; to
endeavor to drive by steady pressure, without striking; -- opposed to
<ant>draw</ant>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Sidelong had <qex>pushed</qex> a mountain from his seat.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To thrust the points of the horns against; to
gore.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If the ox shall <qex>push</qex> a manservant or maidservant, . . .
the ox shall be stoned.</q> <rj><qau>Ex. xxi. 32.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To press or urge forward; to drive; to
<xex>push</xex> an objection too far.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧ To <xex>push</xex>
his fortune.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ambition <qex>pushes</qex> the soul to such actions as are apt to
procure honor to the actor.</q> <rj><qau>Spectator.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We are <qex>pushed</qex> for an answer.</q>
<rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To bear hard upon; to perplex; to
embarrass.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To importune; to press with solicitation; to
tease.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To push down</b></col>, <cd>to overthrow by pushing or
impulse.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Push</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Push
<hw>Push</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make a thrust; to
shove; <as>as, to <ex>push</ex> with the horns or with a
sword</as>.</def> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To make an advance, attack, or effort; to be
energetic; <as>as, a man must <ex>push</ex> in order to
succeed</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>At the time of the end shall the kind of the south <qex>push</qex>
at him and the king of the north shall come against him.</q>
<rj><qau>Dan. xi. 40.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>War seemed asleep for nine long years; at length⟦br⟧
Both sides resolved to <qex>push</qex>, we tried our strength.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To burst pot, as a bud or shoot.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To push on</b></col>, <cd>to drive or urge forward; to
hasten.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The rider <qex>pushed</qex> on at a rapid pace.</q> <rj><qau>Sir
W. Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Push</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Push
<hw>Push</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A thrust with a pointed
instrument, or with the end of a thing.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Any thrust. pressure, impulse, or force, or force
applied; a shove; <as>as, to give the ball the first
<ex>push</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>An assault or attack; an effort; an attempt; hence,
the time or occasion for action.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Exact reformation is not perfected at the first
<qex>push</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When it comes to the <qex>push</qex>, 'tis no more than talk.</q>
<rj><qau>L' Estrange.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The faculty of overcoming obstacles; aggressive
energy; <as>as, he has <ex>push</ex>, or he has no
<ex>push</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- See <er>Thrust</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Push</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Push
<hw>Push</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A crowd; a company or clique of
associates; a gang.</def> <mark>[Slang]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Push button</ent>⟦br⟧
